This article discusses the response of the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) to Hurricane Maria in Puerto Rico, which made landfall a year ago. FEMA, along with other federal partners, provided immediate aid to the island, including food, water, and shelter. The agency remains in Puerto Rico to this day, working towards long-term recovery efforts and investing billions of dollars in aid. The article also highlights the record-breaking and catastrophic nature of the 2017 disaster season, which included hurricanes Harvey, Irma, and Maria, as well as wildfires in California. FEMA has responded to numerous disasters across the country and provided billions of dollars in assistance. The author emphasizes the importance of disaster preparedness and resilience, and commends the efforts of FEMA and its partners in supporting Puerto Rico and other affected areas.